data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

| Issue | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Works but fragile | Obsolete, use `CancellationToken` |
| Manual signal + lock + queue | Works but race-prone | Use `Channel<T>` |

### Bug in Original Code

There's a **race condition**: if two `Enqueue()` calls happen before `WaitOne()` returns, `Reset()` clears the signal and only **one** item is dequeued — the second is silently lost.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _runTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Clean shutdown — expected
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _runTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();           // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        try
        {
            await _runTask;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Timed out — loop was cancelled
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### Key Migration Decisions

**`Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock`**
— Thread-safe, backpressure-aware, no lost items. One type replaces three.

**`CancellationToken` replaces `Abort()`/`Interrupt()`**
— Cooperative cancellation is the only supported model in .NET 8. `Abort()` will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime — not at compile time.

**`StopAsync` uses a two-phase shutdown**
— First, `Writer.Complete()` lets the loop drain remaining items. If that exceeds the timeout, `CancelAfter` forces exit. This replaces the brittle `Join` → `Abort` pattern.

**`IAsyncDisposable`** — ensures cleanup in `await using` blocks.

### If You Need Synchronous `Stop()` (transitional)

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    StopAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5))
        .AsTask()
        .GetAwaiter()
        .GetResult();
}
```

Use this only at composition roots or legacy call sites — avoid `sync-over-async` deeper in the stack (deadlock risk with `SynchronizationContext`).
